CHAPTER SEVEN

1055
02:12:01,680 --> 02:12:03,200
Teiresias's Prophecy

1056
02:12:05,040 --> 02:12:10,080
If you leave his cows unharmed, 
you will arrive safely in Ithaca.

1057
02:12:11,200 --> 02:12:16,400
But if you hurt those cows, your 
ship and your men will be destroyed.'

1058
02:12:19,040 --> 02:12:24,400
Circe was a very welcoming hostess, and 
we stayed with her for a whole year.  

1059
02:12:25,520 --> 02:12:28,960
But as the months passed and the 
long days of summer returned,  

1060
02:12:29,520 --> 02:12:35,360
my companions became anxious that I had 
forgotten my home in Ithaca. "Why are we  

1061
02:12:35,360 --> 02:12:42,480
still here on Circe's island?" they asked me 
one day. "It is time to continue our voyage."

1062
02:12:44,240 --> 02:12:50,400
That night I spoke to Circe. I told 
her about my companions' complaints,  

1063
02:12:51,360 --> 02:12:53,440
and she agreed to help us with our voyage.  

1064
02:12:54,800 --> 02:13:02,400
"But first," she said, "you must visit the 
Underworld and talk to blind old Teiresias.  

1065
02:13:03,280 --> 02:13:09,440
Although he is dead, his prophecies are 
as true as they were during his lifetime."

1066
02:13:11,040 --> 02:13:17,120
This news broke my heart. I nearly chose 
to end my life there in Circe's house  

1067
02:13:17,760 --> 02:13:20,720
to escape the awful journey 
to the world of the dead.  

1068
02:13:22,160 --> 02:13:29,840
But finally I asked her, "How can I find the 
way? No one has ever sailed a ship into Hell."

1069
02:13:30,480 --> 02:13:35,840
"Do not worry. The north wind 
will blow you to the right place.  

1070
02:13:36,880 --> 02:13:44,160
At the edge of the world, you will see a place 
where tall trees grow. Land your ship there  

1071
02:13:44,880 --> 02:13:48,000
and the ghosts of the 
Underworld will come to you."

1072
02:13:50,000 --> 02:13:53,360
She told me what to do and say when I reached that  

1073
02:13:53,360 --> 02:13:59,440
terrible place. She promised that Teiresias 
would tell me the route of my journey home.

1074
02:14:01,120 --> 02:14:04,880
Waking everyone up in the morning, 
I shouted, "Hurry, my friends,  

1075
02:14:05,440 --> 02:14:07,840
and say goodbye to your comfortable beds.  

1076
02:14:08,640 --> 02:14:14,400
It is time to go. Circe has given us 
instructions for the next part of our journey."

1077
02:14:16,000 --> 02:14:22,080
My brave companions were happy to make their 
way back to the ship. But even this time I  

1078
02:14:22,080 --> 02:14:29,440
did not lead everyone away safely. Elpenor was 
the youngest in our group, and not very clever.  

1079
02:14:30,720 --> 02:14:37,520
The night before, after too much wine, he had 
decided to sleep on the roof because the air  

1080
02:14:37,520 --> 02:14:44,240
was fresher there. Woken in the morning by the 
noise of our departure, he jumped up suddenly  

1081
02:14:45,120 --> 02:14:54,000
and fell off the roof. The fall broke his neck. 
When we went to help him, we found him dead.

1082
02:14:54,000 --> 02:15:00,880
By the ship, I told the men that our voyage 
would not take us straight home. When they  

1083
02:15:00,880 --> 02:15:07,440
heard that our destination was the world of 
the dead, they were filled with terror. But  

1084
02:15:07,440 --> 02:15:11,520
they could say nothing to change the 
fate that the gods had chosen for us.

1085
02:15:13,120 --> 02:15:19,680
Circe gave us a good wind to fill our 
sails and, a day after leaving Aeaea,  

1086
02:15:19,680 --> 02:15:27,120
we reached a dark land at the edge of the world. 
There we found the place that Circe had described,  

1087
02:15:27,840 --> 02:15:34,960
where tall trees grow. I landed the ship and 
started to follow Circe's instructions for calling  

1088
02:15:34,960 --> 02:15:43,840
the dead. I dug a hole in the ground, the size of 
a man's arm. Into this hole I poured milk, water  

1089
02:15:44,640 --> 02:15:51,680
and sweet wine. I prayed to the dead and 
sacrificed two fine sheep from my ship.  

1090
02:15:52,960 --> 02:16:00,480
As their blood poured into the hole, ghosts 
started to come up from the earth - young girls,  

1091
02:16:01,520 --> 02:16:05,120
old men, and soldiers killed in war.  

1092
02:16:06,640 --> 02:16:13,680
They were making a strange noise, and cold 
fear ran through me. I guarded the hole with  

1093
02:16:13,680 --> 02:16:20,400
my sword held tightly. I did not want any 
ghosts to get to the blood before Teiresias.

1094
02:16:22,640 --> 02:16:26,480
Suddenly, I recognised the ghost of Elpenor.  

1095
02:16:27,760 --> 02:16:34,240
In our hurry to leave Circe's island, we had not 
burnt his body or built a mound of earth for him.  

1096
02:16:35,200 --> 02:16:42,399
I called out, "Elpenor! You have reached here more 
quickly on foot than we did in our fast ship."

1097
02:16:43,920 --> 02:16:53,680
"Yes, master, but you rushed away from Aeaea too 
fast. Please, when you return, remember my body.  

1098
02:16:54,720 --> 02:16:59,840
Burn it on the beach with my sword, and 
build a mound of earth in my memory.  

1099
02:17:00,479 --> 02:17:05,200
At the top, plant the oar that I used 
on the ship with my dear companions."

1100
02:17:06,560 --> 02:17:10,560
"I will do all that you ask, 
dear Elpenor," I replied.

1101
02:17:12,160 --> 02:17:14,479
Teiresias was not far behind him.

1102
02:17:16,000 --> 02:17:24,960
"Odysseus, son of Laertes, why have 
you left the sunlight to visit the dead  

1103
02:17:24,960 --> 02:17:31,760
in this sad, dark place? If you want 
a prophecy, step away from the blood.  

1104
02:17:33,200 --> 02:17:42,240
I will tell you your future after I have drunk."

1105
02:17:42,240 --> 02:17:50,719
I let him drink the blood, and he soon 
said, "My lord Odysseus, you want an  

1106
02:17:50,720 --> 02:17:57,760
easy route home. But Poseidon is angry 
about your cruel treatment of his son,  

1107
02:17:58,319 --> 02:18:09,759
the Cyclops, and he is going to make your journey 
hard. You and your men will finally reach home,  

1108
02:18:09,760 --> 02:18:16,720
though, if you can control your hunger 
when you come to the island of Thrinacie.  

1109
02:18:18,800 --> 02:18:27,280
There you will find the fat cows of the Sun 
god, who can see everything on his daily  

1110
02:18:27,280 --> 02:18:37,840
journey across the sky. If you leave his cows 
unharmed, you will arrive safely in Ithaca.  

1111
02:18:38,800 --> 02:18:49,280
But if you hurt those cows, your ship and 
your men will be destroyed. You yourself  

1112
02:18:49,280 --> 02:18:58,559
will return home on a foreign ship and find 
your family in terrible trouble. You will find  

1113
02:18:58,560 --> 02:19:05,840
arrogant suitors in your palace, eating your 
food and demanding marriage with your wife.  

1114
02:19:07,840 --> 02:19:14,240
You will kill the suitors for their crimes. 
But then you must start another journey.  

1115
02:19:15,200 --> 02:19:23,439
Take an oar and travel until you find a 
place where the people know nothing about  

1116
02:19:23,439 --> 02:19:32,879
the sea and ships and the use of salt in their 
food. You will meet a man who calls your oar  

1117
02:19:33,439 --> 02:19:42,960
a farm tool. That will be your sign. Plant 
your oar in the earth and sacrifice a sheep,  

1118
02:19:44,000 --> 02:19:54,880
a cow and a pig to the great god Poseidon. After 
this, you can go home. You will have a long life,  

1119
02:19:55,439 --> 02:20:02,319
and you will die peacefully of old 
age, far from the terrors of the sea."

1120
02:20:04,399 --> 02:20:16,947
"So this is the fate that the gods have chosen 
for me," I said. "Thank you, Teiresias."

1121
02:20:16,947 --> 02:20:24,240
As Teiresias went back to the Underworld, the 
ghost of my mother, Anticleia, came towards  

1122
02:20:24,240 --> 02:20:33,120
me. I was deeply upset to see her there. She had 
been alive when I left Ithaca for the war in Troy.  

1123
02:20:34,080 --> 02:20:43,840
"Mother, tell me what happened to you," I cried. 
"What death brought you to this terrible place?"

1124
02:20:45,680 --> 02:20:52,400
"It was sadness that killed me, Odysseus, my 
child. I missed your wise and gentle ways,  

1125
02:20:53,200 --> 02:20:58,880
and life gave me no pleasure. In 
death, I have escaped that pain."

1126
02:21:00,319 --> 02:21:02,399
I tried to put my arms around her,  

1127
02:21:03,200 --> 02:21:07,679
but there was nothing to hold. My 
arms went straight through her.

1128
02:21:08,399 --> 02:21:15,040
"You cannot touch me, Odysseus. When life 
leaves the body, we become no more than a dream.  

1129
02:21:16,399 --> 02:21:22,879
But go now, return to the world of 
the sun, and find your way back home."

1130
02:21:24,240 --> 02:21:25,840
"But what can you tell me about home,"  

1131
02:21:26,800 --> 02:21:32,400
I asked her. "How is the rest of 
the family? Are they safe and well?"

1132
02:21:34,160 --> 02:21:40,720
"Penelope and Telemachus are still living in your 
palace, trying to keep your lands safe from the  

1133
02:21:40,720 --> 02:21:48,800
greedy suitors. But your father Laertes lives 
a sad and lonely life, alone on his fruit farm.  

1134
02:21:49,760 --> 02:21:56,479
He never goes down to the city now. In winter 
he sleeps on the floor by his fire, without a  

1135
02:21:56,479 --> 02:22:03,759
bed or a blanket to keep him warm. In summer, he 
sleeps under the fruit trees in a bed of leaves.  

1136
02:22:04,800 --> 02:22:10,000
As old age presses down on him, he 
thinks of nothing except your return."

1137
02:22:12,319 --> 02:22:19,040
Soon Persephone, Queen of the Underworld, drove 
away my mother and the other women ghosts who  

1138
02:22:19,040 --> 02:22:29,920
were with her. In shock, I saw another ghost that 
I recognised - Agamemnon. He drank the dark blood  

1139
02:22:29,920 --> 02:22:36,720
and stretched out his hand towards me. But all 
the strength had left the body that had been  

1140
02:22:36,720 --> 02:22:43,680
so powerful, and he could not reach me. He and 
I looked at each other with tears in our eyes.  

1141
02:22:45,120 --> 02:22:50,399
Finally, I said, "Great king, what 
terrible fate has brought you here?  

1142
02:22:51,439 --> 02:22:57,280
Were you killed in a storm on your way home 
from Troy, or in a fight on enemy lands?"

1143
02:22:58,720 --> 02:23:08,640
"No, my friend," Agamemnon replied. "I was 
murdered when I reached my homeland by my cousin  

1144
02:23:09,840 --> 02:23:19,520
Aegisthus. Aegisthus welcomed me to my palace, 
then killed me like a sheep for a sacrifice.  

1145
02:23:21,040 --> 02:23:26,399
My companions were cut down too, and 
the floor of the hall swam with blood.  

1146
02:23:27,840 --> 02:23:35,360
You saw the deaths of many fine men at Troy, 
Odysseus, but none were as pitiful as ours.

1147
02:23:36,640 --> 02:23:43,760
"And, worst of all, my wife 
Clytaemnestra was there watching.  

1148
02:23:45,600 --> 02:23:52,480
When I was dying, with a sword in my chest, 
she turned away coldly and joined her lover,  

1149
02:23:53,200 --> 02:23:59,840
Aegisthus. She did not even close 
my eyes or mouth for me in death."

1150
02:24:01,600 --> 02:24:07,360
"Poor man!" I cried. "Zeus has 
been a cruel enemy to your family,  

1151
02:24:08,080 --> 02:24:11,040
using the tricks of women 
to destroy your happiness.  

1152
02:24:12,240 --> 02:24:19,679
Your brother s wife Helen caused the Trojan 
War, and now your own wife has sent you here."

1153
02:24:20,479 --> 02:24:31,359
"Yes," replied Agamemnon. "Never tell a woman 
all your secrets, Odysseus, not even your wife,  

1154
02:24:32,479 --> 02:24:41,839
because one day she may turn against you. When 
you reach home, do not sail openly into port.  

1155
02:24:42,880 --> 02:24:50,560
Hide your return until you are sure that you are 
safe. But you are luckier than I was, my friend.  

1156
02:24:51,680 --> 02:24:57,440
Your own wife, Penelope, has a 
loyal heart and a wise head."

1157
02:24:59,680 --> 02:25:02,160
I said a sad goodbye to Agamemnon.  

1158
02:25:03,280 --> 02:25:09,840
I had learned what I needed to in this 
terrible place. It was time to leave.

1159
02:25:13,359 --> 02:25:21,920
I called to my men to get the ship ready, and soon 
we were on our way. With a good wind in our sails,  

1160
02:25:21,920 --> 02:25:27,040
we quickly reached Aeaea, the 
island of beautiful Circe.  

1161
02:25:28,479 --> 02:25:36,240
We found Elpenors body and took it to the 
highest place on the coast. There we built a fire  

1162
02:25:36,240 --> 02:25:42,080
and placed his body on it. We watched 
sadly as the flames surrounded him.  

1163
02:25:43,600 --> 02:25:47,840
When the fire was dead, we covered 
the place with a mound of earth  

1164
02:25:48,479 --> 02:25:56,240
and planted Elpenor's oar on top. I prayed that 
his death would be the last on our journey home.

1165
02:25:57,920 --> 02:26:05,840
Circe had noticed our return, and came now with 
her servants, carrying bread, meat and wine.  

1166
02:26:06,720 --> 02:26:11,440
We had a good meal on the beach, in 
preparation for our voyage the next day.  

1167
02:26:13,120 --> 02:26:20,960
When it grew dark, my men went to sleep by 
the ship, but Circe held me back. She wanted  

1168
02:26:20,960 --> 02:26:29,520
to warn me about the dangers of the voyage ahead. 
"Listen to my advice, Odysseus, and hopefully you  

1169
02:26:29,520 --> 02:26:39,120
will remember it when you need it most. You will 
soon meet the Sirens. They sit on their island,  

1170
02:26:39,120 --> 02:26:47,200
singing to the sailors who pass. They ask people 
to come closer, and their voices are so beautiful  

1171
02:26:47,200 --> 02:26:56,639
that the sailors cannot refuse. But be careful. 
Piles of dead bodies lie all around that island.  

1172
02:26:57,680 --> 02:27:06,640
Its rocks destroy any ship that goes near. 
But it is possible to sail past safely.  

1173
02:27:07,680 --> 02:27:14,080
Put wax in the ears of your crew, so that 
they cannot hear the Sirens' magical song.  

1174
02:27:15,359 --> 02:27:21,599
If you wish to hear it yourself, your 
men must tie you tightly to the ship.  

1175
02:27:22,880 --> 02:27:31,040
They must not free you until the danger 
has passed. When the Sirens are behind you,  

1176
02:27:31,040 --> 02:27:38,560
you will have to choose between two routes. 
One takes you to the Moving Rocks, which crash  

1177
02:27:38,560 --> 02:27:45,840
together whenever a ship sails between them. Even 
the birds cannot fly through this place safely,  

1178
02:27:45,840 --> 02:27:55,120
but lose a wing or a tail when the rocks squeeze 
tight. For sailors, there is no hope of escape.  

1179
02:27:57,200 --> 02:28:04,559
In the other direction lie two rocks. One 
is so tall and steep that no one could climb  

1180
02:28:04,560 --> 02:28:12,320
to the top of it. Half way up there is a 
cave, and this is the home of the monster  

1181
02:28:13,439 --> 02:28:23,120
Scylla. She is a terrible sight, with twelve 
feet and six long necks, each ending in a head  

1182
02:28:23,120 --> 02:28:30,479
full of teeth as sharp as knives. She lies 
in her cave, stretching her long necks down  

1183
02:28:30,479 --> 02:28:38,319
to the sea in search of seals and fish to eat. 
No crew has ever passed her without losing men.  

1184
02:28:39,359 --> 02:28:47,200
She always catches a sailor in each of her 
six mouths. The other rock is not as high,  

1185
02:28:47,920 --> 02:28:52,000
and is only a short distance across 
the water from Scylla's cave.  

1186
02:28:53,439 --> 02:29:01,120
A fruit tree grows from the rock, and below it 
the awful Charybdis pulls down the dark water to  

1187
02:29:01,120 --> 02:29:08,640
the sea floor. Three times a day she pulls it 
down, and three times she throws it up again.  

1188
02:29:09,760 --> 02:29:16,399
I pray that the gods keep you away from her, 
because not even the sea-god Poseidon could  

1189
02:29:16,399 --> 02:29:24,639
save your ship from her violent seas. 
No, you must stay close to Scylla's rock  

1190
02:29:24,640 --> 02:29:32,800
and sail past as quickly as you can. It is better 
to lose six of your men than your whole crew."

1191
02:29:33,520 --> 02:29:40,320
"Yes," I replied. "But is there really no way 
to protect all my men from these two monsters?"

1192
02:29:41,520 --> 02:29:47,281
"Are you still looking for trouble, 
Odysseus, after all that you have suffered?  

1193
02:29:48,479 --> 02:29:54,959
Scylla is a monster of great power. 
She cannot die. You will waste time  

1194
02:29:54,960 --> 02:30:02,080
if you try to fight her. Then she will be 
able to take even more of your men. No,  

1195
02:30:03,439 --> 02:30:10,160
you must accept your fate. Sacrifice six 
of your men and the rest will be safe."

1196
02:30:12,399 --> 02:30:20,799
As she finished speaking, the sun came up. I said 
goodbye to Circe and went back to my companions.  

1197
02:30:22,240 --> 02:30:29,280
We untied the ship and were soon on 
our way. We made good progress as the  

1198
02:30:29,280 --> 02:30:34,800
men pulled on their oars. It was time 
to prepare them for the danger ahead.

1199
02:30:38,960 --> 02:30:46,480
"My friends, Circe has given me advice for the 
rest of our journey. I must share it with you.  

1200
02:30:48,000 --> 02:30:54,560
First, we will come to the island of the Sirens. 
I will protect your ears from the magic of the  

1201
02:30:54,560 --> 02:31:03,840
Sirens' song. But one of us should listen. Tie me 
very tightly to the ship so that I cannot escape.  

1202
02:31:04,880 --> 02:31:11,040
If I complain, tie me more tightly. 
Do not take the ship near the island,  

1203
02:31:11,040 --> 02:31:18,240
even if I command it a hundred times. The 
rocks destroy all ships that go near."

1204
02:31:20,560 --> 02:31:24,000
I took some wax and made it warm in my hands.  

1205
02:31:25,439 --> 02:31:30,319
Then I pushed a little into everyone's 
ears, so that they could hear nothing.  

1206
02:31:31,760 --> 02:31:39,040
When this was done, the men tied my hands and 
feet to the ship, and we were ready to continue.

1207
02:31:41,359 --> 02:31:48,080
The Sirens' island soon came into view. 
We saw three strange women on the island,  

1208
02:31:48,080 --> 02:31:55,840
with beautiful human faces but the bodies 
of birds. They started their magical song,  

1209
02:31:56,479 --> 02:32:03,200
and it was the most beautiful music in the 
world. I was filled with desire to hear more.  

1210
02:32:04,960 --> 02:32:12,880
When they asked me to come to them, I wanted to 
with all my heart. I ordered my men to untie me,  

1211
02:32:13,920 --> 02:32:20,560
but of course they could not hear. I tried 
to break free, but they tied me more tightly.  

1212
02:32:22,080 --> 02:32:26,720
Sadly, I watched the men take me further 
and further from the Sirens' island.  

1213
02:32:28,160 --> 02:32:37,840
Finally, they untied me and took out the wax 
from their ears. With Circe's help, we were safe.

1214
02:32:38,399 --> 02:32:41,200
But there was no time to 
discuss what had happened.  

1215
02:32:42,160 --> 02:32:47,040
We saw rough water ahead, and heard 
the thunder of waves against rocks.  

1216
02:32:47,840 --> 02:32:53,760
The crew were so frightened that the oars fell 
from their hands. I walked around the ship,  

1217
02:32:53,760 --> 02:33:01,360
saying, "We have met trouble before, my friends. 
With my help, you escaped the Cyclops's cave.  

1218
02:33:02,240 --> 02:33:08,719
Today you must follow my orders again. We are 
going to go as close as possible to the higher  

1219
02:33:08,720 --> 02:33:16,241
rock, keeping the ship away from the rough water. 
Stay at your oars and pull as hard as you can."

1220
02:33:17,760 --> 02:33:25,439
The crew obeyed. I did not tell them about Scylla, 
because fear of the monster would stop them from  

1221
02:33:25,439 --> 02:33:32,160
pulling on their oars. I stood at the front of 
the ship, hoping to get the first view of those  

1222
02:33:32,160 --> 02:33:40,240
six long necks. I looked until my eyes 
grew tired, but I could see nothing.

1223
02:33:42,240 --> 02:33:47,840
Then, suddenly, Charybdis threw up 
the water from the deep sea floor.  

1224
02:33:49,200 --> 02:33:55,200
Salt water fell down on us like rain, and 
the top of the sea was like boiling water.

1225
02:33:56,319 --> 02:34:01,840
Then she pulled the water down again, and we 
could see the sand at the bottom of the sea.

1226
02:34:03,280 --> 02:34:09,759
My men were pale with fear. Then, while 
everyone was looking at Charybdis,  

1227
02:34:10,560 --> 02:34:16,560
Scylla stretched her necks down from her cave 
and caught six of my strongest men in her mouths.  

1228
02:34:17,920 --> 02:34:24,880
Their arms and legs waved pitifully in the air 
as they called for help. But we could do nothing  

1229
02:34:24,880 --> 02:34:32,400
to save them. In seconds, the monster had carried 
them up to her cave and started her terrible meal.

1230
02:34:33,920 --> 02:34:42,640
We continued sadly on our way, and soon we saw 
the lovely island of Thrinacie. As we came near  

1231
02:34:42,640 --> 02:34:50,880
the beach, we could heard the sound of cows. 
I remembered the words of Teiresias and said,  

1232
02:34:50,880 --> 02:34:58,160
"Listen carefully, my friends. In the Underworld, 
Teiresias warned me about this island. There is  

1233
02:34:58,160 --> 02:35:06,240
a greater danger here than any that we have met 
before. Sail past the island. We should not land."

1234
02:35:07,840 --> 02:35:15,520
My men were very upset. Eurylochus 
shouted, "Do you never get tired, Odysseus?  

1235
02:35:16,560 --> 02:35:21,600
How can you tell us not to land here, 
after everything that has happened today?  

1236
02:35:22,479 --> 02:35:30,879
You must be made of iron! It is nearly sunset, 
and we are tired and hungry. If we continue past  

1237
02:35:30,880 --> 02:35:37,040
this island, we will be at sea all night 
- there is no other land near here.  

1238
02:35:37,840 --> 02:35:45,840
And storms are always worse at night. Do you 
really want the winds to destroy our ship? You are  

1239
02:35:45,840 --> 02:35:53,840
crazy. We should land here and cook our supper. 
In the morning, we can go back to the open sea."

1240
02:35:55,439 --> 02:36:00,719
The rest of the crew agreed with him, 
and I realized that the gods had already  

1241
02:36:00,720 --> 02:36:10,320
decided our fate. "I am one against many, 
Eurylochus. I cannot refuse your demands.  

1242
02:36:11,840 --> 02:36:17,040
But I ask every one of you to promise that 
you will not harm the animals on the island.  

1243
02:36:18,240 --> 02:36:22,000
Sit peacefully and eat the 
food that Circe has given us.  

1244
02:36:23,120 --> 02:36:28,080
If you eat anything else, I cannot 
save you from a disastrous end."

1245
02:36:32,160 --> 02:36:39,359
When everyone on the ship had given me their 
promise, we landed on the Sun-god's island. We ate  

1246
02:36:39,359 --> 02:36:45,439
a good supper, but the conversation kept returning 
to the men that Scylla had taken from us.  

1247
02:36:47,200 --> 02:36:53,840
During the night, a storm blew up, and 
in the morning it was not safe to sail.  

1248
02:36:55,520 --> 02:37:00,960
I called my companions to a meeting and said, 
"We still have plenty of food on the ship.  

1249
02:37:01,920 --> 02:37:09,279
Keep your hands off the cows on this island, or 
disaster will follow. They belong to the Sun-god,  

1250
02:37:10,000 --> 02:37:13,280
who can see everything on his 
daily journey across the sky."

1251
02:37:15,439 --> 02:37:23,679
The men agreed willingly. But the storm 
did not stop. For a whole month it blew,  

1252
02:37:24,640 --> 02:37:33,040
and we were unable to leave the island. While our 
bread and wine lasted, the men obeyed my orders.  

1253
02:37:34,240 --> 02:37:41,120
When there was nothing more to eat, they went 
fishing and caught birds from the trees, but they  

1254
02:37:41,120 --> 02:37:48,399
were still hungry. I hoped that one of the gods 
would take pity on us and show me a way to escape.  

1255
02:37:50,000 --> 02:37:53,200
I found a quiet place, out of the wind, to pray.  

1256
02:37:54,960 --> 02:37:59,840
But when I had finished, the 
gods sent me into a deep sleep.

1257
02:38:01,920 --> 02:38:10,319
While I slept, Eurylochus was causing trouble down 
by the ship. "No death is pleasant," he argued,  

1258
02:38:10,960 --> 02:38:16,560
"but a death from hunger is the 
worst. I say we should eat those cows.  

1259
02:38:17,439 --> 02:38:23,120
We can sacrifice them to the gods, and promise 
to give all our treasure to the Sun god  

1260
02:38:23,120 --> 02:38:29,599
when we return to Ithaca. If he is still 
angry with us, let him destroy our ship.  

1261
02:38:30,720 --> 02:38:35,520
A quick death at sea is easier than a 
slow and painful one on this island."

1262
02:38:36,560 --> 02:38:43,520
The rest of the crew agreed to his plan. Quickly, 
they brought the cows together and sacrificed them  

1263
02:38:43,520 --> 02:38:51,201
to the gods. They had no wine to pour over the 
meat as it cooked, so they used seawater instead.

1264
02:38:53,040 --> 02:38:59,359
As I woke from my sleep, I smelled 
the meat cooking on the fire. "So  

1265
02:38:59,359 --> 02:39:06,639
the gods have decided to ruin me," I 
cried. "There is no hope for us now!"

1266
02:39:08,560 --> 02:39:12,880
High in the sky, the Sun god 
had seen my companions' crime.  

1267
02:39:14,080 --> 02:39:21,040
He went to Zeus in anger, saying, "Odysseus 
and his followers have killed my fine cows.  

1268
02:39:22,240 --> 02:39:28,319
You must punish them, as they deserve. 
If you leave their actions unpunished,  

1269
02:39:28,319 --> 02:39:34,080
I will disappear from the sky and 
shine on the dead in the Underworld."

1270
02:39:35,439 --> 02:39:42,240
"Shine on us here on Olympus and 
on the world of men," Zeus replied.  

1271
02:39:42,960 --> 02:39:45,840
"You can be sure that I 
will punish the criminals."

1272
02:39:47,520 --> 02:39:49,760
This was their conversation on Olympus.  

1273
02:39:50,960 --> 02:39:55,359
Calypso heard about it from Hermes 
and later reported it to me.

1274
02:39:57,520 --> 02:40:02,800
Down on the Sun god's island, the men were 
frightened. They could already see the  

1275
02:40:02,800 --> 02:40:08,800
signs of the gods' anger. The skins of the dead 
animals were moving magically around the beach,  

1276
02:40:09,439 --> 02:40:13,279
and the pieces of meat on the fire were 
calling out to each other like cows.  

1277
02:40:14,800 --> 02:40:22,000
But we could do nothing to change the situation. 
The cows were dead. The damage had been done.

1278
02:40:24,640 --> 02:40:29,680
For six days, the men ate the meat of 
the Sun-god's cows. On the seventh,  

1279
02:40:30,319 --> 02:40:37,920
the wind dropped and it was safe to sail. With 
fear in our hearts, we took our ship out to sea.  

1280
02:40:39,520 --> 02:40:45,760
Almost immediately, a cloud formed above the 
ship, making a dark shadow on the sea around us.  

1281
02:40:47,120 --> 02:40:54,080
Then came the wind. With the force of a wild 
animal, it attacked us. It pulled the sail from  

1282
02:40:54,080 --> 02:41:00,800
the ship in seconds. Wood came crashing down onto 
the sailors below and one man was knocked into  

1283
02:41:00,800 --> 02:41:09,440
the sea. Worse followed, as Zeus struck the ship 
with lightning. The whole ship shook violently.  

1284
02:41:10,720 --> 02:41:16,240
The men held on tightly, but one by 
one they were thrown from the ship.  

1285
02:41:16,240 --> 02:41:21,599
They were pulled this way and that in the water 
until they went down under the waves forever.

1286
02:41:24,479 --> 02:41:32,000
I alone was left on board. But soon the strength 
of the enormous waves broke the ship into pieces.  

1287
02:41:33,680 --> 02:41:41,279
Luckily, I managed to climb onto a broken piece 
of wood, and I held on tightly. All night I was  

1288
02:41:41,279 --> 02:41:48,559
blown around by the wind. At sunrise I saw that 
I had been driven back to the rocks of Scylla  

1289
02:41:49,600 --> 02:41:56,880
and Charybdis. Charybdis was beginning to pull the 
waters down and I was swept towards a great hole  

1290
02:41:56,880 --> 02:42:03,440
in the sea. Just in time, I managed to catch 
a branch of the tree that grew from the rock.  

1291
02:42:04,640 --> 02:42:12,319
I could not get my feet onto the tree, 
but I hung by my arms, hour after hour.  

1292
02:42:12,319 --> 02:42:18,160
Finally, my wait was over. Charybdis threw 
up the wood that had saved me from the storm.  

1293
02:42:18,960 --> 02:42:27,040
I let myself fall back into the sea, swam 
to the wood and climbed back on. Luckily,  

1294
02:42:27,040 --> 02:42:32,479
Scylla did not see me, because there was 
nothing to protect me from her greedy mouths.

1295
02:42:34,640 --> 02:42:40,479
'I was at sea for another nine days, until the 
waves carried me to the shores of Calypso's  

1296
02:42:40,479 --> 02:42:48,799
island. She was kind to me and gave me a 
home. But I have already told you about  

1297
02:42:48,800 --> 02:42:57,600
my life with Calypso, good Phaeacians. I 
have reached the end of my story.'
 
 
 

1298
02:43:01,920 --> 02:43:02,640
CHAPTER EIGHT

1299
02:43:03,920 --> 02:43:04,560
Coming Home

1300
02:43:06,880 --> 02:43:11,520
'Look around you, Odysseus. Do 
you not recognise this beach,  

1301
02:43:12,560 --> 02:43:16,081
those rocks, and that tree on the hills above?'

1302
02:43:18,720 --> 02:43:25,040
When Odysseus had finished, the hall was 
silent until Alcinous said, 'Odysseus,  

1303
02:43:26,000 --> 02:43:33,040
you have suffered greatly. But I am sure that 
you will reach home safely now, with our help.'

1304
02:43:34,399 --> 02:43:41,359
Then he spoke to his Phaeacian guests. 'Friends,' 
he said, 'we have already given our guests fine  

1305
02:43:41,359 --> 02:43:49,839
gifts, but does this man not deserve more after 
all his troubles? Go now and bring him some more  

1306
02:43:49,840 --> 02:43:56,240
treasure from your home. Later we will ask 
the common people to pay for these gifts;  

1307
02:43:57,279 --> 02:44:00,479
we do not want any man's generosity to ruin him.'

1308
02:44:02,800 --> 02:44:08,400
The next day the Phaeacians came to the 
port with their gifts of gold and silver,  

1309
02:44:08,960 --> 02:44:13,120
and Alcinous himself helped to 
put the gifts safely on the ship.  

1310
02:44:14,880 --> 02:44:18,720
Then they all returned to the 
palace for more food and music,  

1311
02:44:19,359 --> 02:44:26,799
as the voyage was not going to start until 
sunset. All day Odysseus kept looking at the sun.  

1312
02:44:28,240 --> 02:44:35,599
He was like a farmer who has worked hard in the 
fields all day; sunset is a welcome sight to a  

1313
02:44:35,600 --> 02:44:42,560
man with tired legs and an empty stomach - it 
is the time to stop work and go home for supper.  

1314
02:44:43,600 --> 02:44:50,880
In the same way, Odysseus welcomed sunset that 
day. As soon as the sun had sunk below the sea,  

1315
02:44:50,880 --> 02:45:00,560
he said, 'Alcinous, great king, let me say 
goodbye. You have given me the two things  

1316
02:45:00,560 --> 02:45:08,720
that I most wanted - valuable gifts and a crew 
to take me home. I pray that the gods bring  

1317
02:45:08,720 --> 02:45:14,640
you and your family all the happiness that you 
deserve, and keep your people safe from harm.'

1318
02:45:17,359 --> 02:45:23,920
Odysseus and the Phaeacians walked down to the 
port, and the servants carried bread and wine for  

1319
02:45:23,920 --> 02:45:32,640
the voyage. On the ship, a blanket was spread out 
for Odysseus to sleep on. Then, after praying to  

1320
02:45:32,640 --> 02:45:40,161
the gods, Odysseus climbed on board. He lay down 
on the blanket and the crew sat at their oars.  

1321
02:45:41,279 --> 02:45:47,279
As the ship left the port, Odysseus immediately 
fell into a deep and peaceful sleep.

1322
02:45:49,120 --> 02:45:53,040
And now, like a team of four 
horses in a chariot race,  

1323
02:45:53,600 --> 02:46:00,720
the ship raced through the water towards Ithaca. 
After a journey of magical speed, it arrived  

1324
02:46:00,720 --> 02:46:07,760
on the coast of Ithaca just before sunrise. The 
crew found a beach with a large cave beside it.  

1325
02:46:09,040 --> 02:46:17,600
There the Phaeacian oarsmen landed the ship and 
lifted Odysseus, still asleep, onto the sand. They  

1326
02:46:17,600 --> 02:46:23,840
took all his gifts from the ship and piled them 
next to him. Then they started their voyage home.

1327
02:46:28,640 --> 02:46:35,359
Athene threw a fog over the island of Ithaca, so 
that no one noticed Odysseus before she could warn  

1328
02:46:35,359 --> 02:46:43,040
him of the dangers in his palace. As a result, 
when Odysseus woke up he did not recognise his  

1329
02:46:43,040 --> 02:46:50,720
homeland. He jumped to his feet and cried, 'Oh 
no! Whose country have I come to this time?  

1330
02:46:51,760 --> 02:46:59,279
Will they be kind hosts, or dangerous monsters? 
Where can I keep my treasure safe? And what were  

1331
02:46:59,279 --> 02:47:06,240
those dishonest Phaeacians thinking? They promised 
that they would take me home to Ithaca, but  

1332
02:47:06,240 --> 02:47:13,200
instead they have left me in this strange place. 
Let Zeus punish them for breaking their promise.  

1333
02:47:14,399 --> 02:47:20,000
I should look at my treasure too, to 
check that they have not stolen anything.'

1334
02:47:20,000 --> 02:47:26,240
He checked his gifts carefully, 
but none were missing. Just then,  

1335
02:47:27,040 --> 02:47:34,080
Athene came to him, disguised as a good-looking 
young farmworker. Odysseus was very  

1336
02:47:34,080 --> 02:47:37,600
happy to see that the people of the 
island were not monsters, and said,  

1337
02:47:38,399 --> 02:47:43,279
'Good morning, friend. You are the first 
person that I have met in this land.  

1338
02:47:44,560 --> 02:47:51,280
Please help me. I need to find a safe place for 
my treasure. And I need to know where I am.'

1339
02:47:52,800 --> 02:48:00,160
'I am surprised that you do not know this land. 
It is famous in countries far west and far east of  

1340
02:48:00,160 --> 02:48:09,279
here. It is rocky - not a good place for horses 
- but it has good farmland and produces fine  

1341
02:48:09,279 --> 02:48:16,399
sheep and cows. Yes, even far away in 
Troy they know the name of Ithaca.'

1342
02:48:18,319 --> 02:48:21,439
Odysseus's heart filled with happiness  

1343
02:48:21,439 --> 02:48:27,279
when he heard that lovely name, but just 
in time he remembered to be careful.

1344
02:48:28,080 --> 02:48:36,720
'Of course,' he replied, 'even in Crete we have 
heard of Ithaca. Crete has been my home until now.  

1345
02:48:37,600 --> 02:48:42,400
But the king's son tried to take from 
me all the treasure that I won at Troy.  

1346
02:48:43,520 --> 02:48:49,600
It was very unfair. I had 
only one choice - to kill him.  

1347
02:48:50,560 --> 02:48:57,840
But when he was dead, I could not live safely in 
Crete. So I took the first ship that I could find.  

1348
02:48:58,880 --> 02:49:06,240
We were aiming for Pylos, but the wind was too 
strong and we were driven here instead. Last  

1349
02:49:06,240 --> 02:49:13,439
night we slept on this beach. When I woke in 
the morning, the ship and its crew had gone.'

1350
02:49:14,960 --> 02:49:20,319
Athene smiled at Odysseus's story, 
then changed into her true form.  

1351
02:49:21,840 --> 02:49:26,080
Odysseus stared in wonder at the 
beautiful goddess in front of him.  

1352
02:49:27,520 --> 02:49:35,760
'So even in your homeland you have not given up 
your tricks, Odysseus! You and I are so similar.  

1353
02:49:36,560 --> 02:49:43,439
You are the cleverest and most resourceful person 
in the world of men, and I am the cleverest  

1354
02:49:43,439 --> 02:49:47,599
and most resourceful of the 
gods. But, though you are clever,  

1355
02:49:48,240 --> 02:49:55,599
you did not realize that the goddess Athene 
was beside you through all your adventures. I  

1356
02:49:56,160 --> 02:50:01,760
made the Phaeacians look after you 
kindly. And now I will help you again.'

1357
02:50:03,680 --> 02:50:09,920
'It is hard to recognise you in all your 
disguises, great goddess,' Odysseus replied.  

1358
02:50:10,960 --> 02:50:17,040
'I remember your kindness at Troy, but have 
I really had much help from you since then?  

1359
02:50:18,399 --> 02:50:23,120
Where were you when the Greek ships were 
separated because of arguments and storms?  

1360
02:50:24,399 --> 02:50:27,200
Where were you when my 
companions were lost at sea?'

1361
02:50:28,479 --> 02:50:32,959
'You must understand that I 
could not act against Poseidon,  

1362
02:50:32,960 --> 02:50:37,120
who was very angry about your 
treatment of his son, the Cyclops.'

1363
02:50:37,840 --> 02:50:42,160
'But tell me, goddess, and I 
pray that you answer me honestly:  

1364
02:50:43,600 --> 02:50:49,840
is this really Ithaca, or were your words 
intended to make me suffer even more?'

1365
02:50:50,960 --> 02:50:55,439
'Look around you, Odysseus. Do 
you not recognise this beach,  

1366
02:50:56,080 --> 02:50:59,359
those rocks, and that tree on the hills above?'

1367
02:51:00,880 --> 02:51:05,600
As she spoke, she lifted the fog 
that was hiding the land from view.  

1368
02:51:06,880 --> 02:51:12,880
Odysseus recognised it at last. He threw 
himself down on the ground and kissed the sand.

1369
02:51:14,160 --> 02:51:19,200
'Come,' said the goddess. 'We must hide 
your treasure in that cave over there.'  

1370
02:51:20,880 --> 02:51:26,400
When everything was safely in the cave, Athene 
warned him about the situation in the palace.  

1371
02:51:27,600 --> 02:51:33,680
'Penelope is surrounded by suitors. They are 
arrogant and greedy men, who will do anything.  

1372
02:51:34,640 --> 02:51:41,359
They are even trying to murder your son 
Telemachus. When it is time to fight them, I will  

1373
02:51:41,359 --> 02:51:48,479
be at your side,' she said. 'But at the moment 
they must not know about your return. I will  

1374
02:51:48,479 --> 02:51:54,959
disguise you as a man so old and poorly dressed 
that even your wife will not recognise you.  

1375
02:51:56,640 --> 02:52:02,560
Go and stay with Eumaeus, the pig farmer. 
He is still loyal to you and Penelope,  

1376
02:52:03,120 --> 02:52:10,240
and he loves Telemachus like a son. He can 
give you the news from the town. And I will  

1377
02:52:10,240 --> 02:52:15,599
bring Telemachus home from Sparta, where he 
has been asking Menelaus for news of you.'

1378
02:52:17,279 --> 02:52:24,880
Athene used her magic to change Odysseus into a 
weak old man. His skin hung loose on his body,  

1379
02:52:25,439 --> 02:52:29,759
his hair was white, and his 
clothes were dirty pieces of cloth.  

1380
02:52:31,359 --> 02:52:36,559
Then she disappeared suddenly, 
hurrying to Telemachus in Sparta.

1381
02:52:40,080 --> 02:52:44,319
Odysseus followed a path up to 
the hills and the home of Eumaeus,  

1382
02:52:44,319 --> 02:52:48,399
the pig farmer, the most loyal 
of all Odysseus's farmworkers.  

1383
02:52:50,160 --> 02:52:56,559
He found Eumaeus near his hut, busy with his 
pigs. There were eight hundred on his farm,  

1384
02:52:57,120 --> 02:53:01,519
although their number was reduced every 
day by the enormous meals at the palace.

1385
02:53:03,200 --> 02:53:10,559
The guard dogs saw Odysseus first and ran 
towards him. Luckily, Eumaeus called them  

1386
02:53:10,560 --> 02:53:17,280
back before they attacked the stranger. 'Those 
dogs almost pulled you to pieces, old man,'  

1387
02:53:18,080 --> 02:53:24,319
he said. 'Then I would have even more 
worries. The situation is bad enough now.  

1388
02:53:25,200 --> 02:53:32,960
I spend my days making my master's pigs fat 
so that other men can eat them. But my good,  

1389
02:53:32,960 --> 02:53:39,040
kind master is probably dying of hunger, lost 
in a foreign land, or perhaps already dead.  

1390
02:53:40,160 --> 02:53:45,680
But come inside. When you have had some food 
and wine, you can tell me about yourself.'

1391
02:53:47,040 --> 02:53:53,200
Inside the hut, Eumaeus offered his guest a 
seat on a pile of sticks with a sheepskin thrown  

1392
02:53:53,200 --> 02:54:02,240
over it. 'Thank you for this warm welcome,' said 
Odysseus. 'I hope that the gods are kind to you.'

1393
02:54:04,000 --> 02:54:08,560
Eumaeus prepared some simple food 
and gave it to Odysseus, saying,  

1394
02:54:09,760 --> 02:54:15,600
'It is not much, I am afraid. But we have 
little left after we have sent all our best  

1395
02:54:15,600 --> 02:54:22,560
pigs to those arrogant men in the palace. 
They want to marry my absent master's wife,  

1396
02:54:22,560 --> 02:54:29,201
but they do not behave like future husbands. 
Instead, they sit around the palace all day.  

1397
02:54:29,840 --> 02:54:37,520
They kill several pigs every night and drink my 
master's wine like water. They must know that my  

1398
02:54:37,520 --> 02:54:42,400
master will never return, because they fear 
no punishment for their unlawful behavior.'

1399
02:54:44,560 --> 02:54:49,840
Odysseus ate the food gratefully, thinking 
about what he would do to those suitors.  

1400
02:54:51,040 --> 02:54:57,600
When he had finished, he asked, 
'So who is your absent master?  

1401
02:54:58,399 --> 02:55:04,319
You seem to have a very good opinion of 
him. Perhaps I have met him on my travels.'

1402
02:55:05,520 --> 02:55:13,840
'His name is Odysseus. It was Odysseus, I should 
say, because he is now lying dead somewhere.  

1403
02:55:15,040 --> 02:55:23,279
He was the kindest of masters and the best of men. 
He owned land here on Ithaca and on the mainland.  

1404
02:55:24,399 --> 02:55:31,519
He was rich in pigs and cows and sheep, and in 
treasure too. But the suitors are destroying  

1405
02:55:31,520 --> 02:55:39,121
his property day by day, and soon there will be 
nothing left. My heart aches when I think of it.  

1406
02:55:40,800 --> 02:55:45,600
But tell me, stranger, who you are. 
What has brought you to this island?'

1407
02:55:47,120 --> 02:55:50,319
Odysseus told him that he 
had been a prince of Crete.  

1408
02:55:51,439 --> 02:55:58,160
He had had an argument with his brother and had to 
leave his homeland. After many years of travel and  

1409
02:55:58,160 --> 02:56:04,080
a lot of bad luck, he now owned nothing in the 
world except the clothes that he was wearing.  

1410
02:56:05,840 --> 02:56:12,160
'I met Odysseus once,' he added. 'He stayed 
at our palace in Crete on the way to Troy.  

1411
02:56:13,680 --> 02:56:21,280
And a few days ago I heard talk of him 
again. There was a ship in Thesprotia  

1412
02:56:21,920 --> 02:56:27,760
waiting to carry him home. The crew were 
expecting to start their voyage this week.'

1413
02:56:28,319 --> 02:56:35,200
'I am sorry for all your troubles, old man,' 
the pig farmer replied. 'But I cannot believe  

1414
02:56:35,200 --> 02:56:43,200
your story about Odysseus. Why are you telling 
such lies? Another man told me a similar story  

1415
02:56:43,200 --> 02:56:48,080
last year, and travellers regularly 
upset Penelope with false information.  

1416
02:56:49,200 --> 02:56:54,559
Odysseus never arrives, and only 
a fool now believes that he will.'

1417
02:56:56,479 --> 02:57:03,679
'If my story proves false, you can throw me from 
the highest rock on this island,' said Odysseus.

1418
02:57:04,960 --> 02:57:09,120
'Zeus would soon punish a man who 
invited a stranger into his home  

1419
02:57:09,120 --> 02:57:12,720
and then killed him for lying,' replied Eumaeus.

1420
02:57:14,319 --> 02:57:18,160
They spent the evening in friendly 
conversation in front of the fire.  

1421
02:57:19,520 --> 02:57:25,280
When it was time for sleep, Eumaeus lent 
Odysseus a thick coat to use as a blanket.  

1422
02:57:26,560 --> 02:57:31,760
Then, always careful of his master's 
property, he went out to sleep with  

1423
02:57:31,760 --> 02:57:36,320
the pigs, to protect them from thieves 
and wild animals during the night.
 
 
 

1424
02:57:40,240 --> 02:57:41,040
CHAPTER NINE

1425
02:57:42,000 --> 02:57:43,520
Telemachus Returns

1426
02:57:44,960 --> 02:57:47,680
'I am not a god,' replied Odysseus.  

1427
02:57:48,640 --> 02:57:53,600
'But I am your father, who has been 
the cause of so many problems for you.'

1428
02:57:56,160 --> 02:58:03,840
Athene now went to Sparta and found Telemachus 
and Peisistratus in the palace of King Menelaus.  

1429
02:58:04,399 --> 02:58:08,559
Peisistratus was asleep, but 
Telemachus was lying awake,  

1430
02:58:09,200 --> 02:58:12,720
worrying about his absent father 
and the problem of the suitors.

1431
02:58:14,399 --> 02:58:21,759
Athene stood near him and said, 'Go back to your 
palace and keep it safe from the greedy suitors.  

1432
02:58:22,960 --> 02:58:28,560
Your mother's father has told her to marry 
Eurymachus, since he is the richest of her  

1433
02:58:28,560 --> 02:58:36,880
suitors. If you do not go home soon, you will 
return to an empty house. But be careful.  

1434
02:58:37,920 --> 02:58:43,439
The suitors have sent a ship to attack you 
on your voyage home. They are waiting for  

1435
02:58:43,439 --> 02:58:49,839
you between Ithaca and the coast of Samos, with 
swords in their hands and murder in their hearts.  

1436
02:58:51,120 --> 02:58:57,519
Make sure that you go home a different way, 
and sail at night so that they cannot see  

1437
02:58:57,520 --> 02:59:04,800
your ship. Get off the ship at a quiet part of 
the coast and go straight to Eumaeus's pig farm,  

1438
02:59:05,600 --> 02:59:09,760
while your crew sail to the port 
and spread the news of your return.'

1439
02:59:12,000 --> 02:59:20,080
When she had delivered her message, she went back 
to Mount Olympus. Telemachus woke Peisistratus  

1440
02:59:20,080 --> 02:59:27,920
with a gentle kick and said, 'Come, my friend, 
we must get the chariot ready and be on our way.'

1441
02:59:27,920 --> 02:59:34,160
'We should leave soon, I agree, Telemachus. 
But it is the middle of the night.  

1442
02:59:34,880 --> 02:59:41,359
We cannot drive in complete darkness, and what 
would Menelaus think if we rushed away like  

1443
02:59:41,359 --> 02:59:49,279
thieves in the night? Can our journey not 
wait until morning?' Telemachus agreed to  

1444
02:59:49,279 --> 02:59:56,399
stay in Sparta for a few more hours. When 
daylight came, he went to speak to his host.  

1445
02:59:58,000 --> 03:00:05,040
'Menelaus,' he said, 'I must go home. But 
I will never forget your kindness to me.'

1446
03:00:06,479 --> 03:00:12,240
'I will not keep you here against your 
wishes,' replied the king. 'But give me  

1447
03:00:12,240 --> 03:00:18,160
time to bring you some gifts. And enjoy 
one last meal with us before you leave.'  

1448
03:00:19,840 --> 03:00:24,480
Menelaus gave him the bowl of fine silver 
that he had promised him the day before.  

1449
03:00:25,520 --> 03:00:32,640
Queen Helen added a present of her own. 'I 
made this dress myself,' she told Telemachus.  

1450
03:00:33,600 --> 03:00:38,080
'It is for your future wife 
to wear on your wedding day.'

1451
03:00:38,080 --> 03:00:41,600
They then had some food, and after the meal  

1452
03:00:41,600 --> 03:00:45,201
Telemachus and Peisistratus 
climbed into their chariot.

1453
03:00:46,560 --> 03:00:52,800
'Goodbye, young friends,' said Menelaus. 
'Give my good wishes to Nestor.'

1454
03:00:54,080 --> 03:00:59,680
'We will,' replied Telemachus. 'I 
only hope that one day I can give  

1455
03:00:59,680 --> 03:01:06,319
your good wishes to my father too, 
and tell him of your kindness to me.'

1456
03:01:06,319 --> 03:01:13,279
As he spoke, an eagle flew across the sky, 
carrying a chicken from a local farm in its feet.  

