03:01:14,880 --> 03:01:19,200
Some farmworkers were chasing 
the eagle, but it gave a cry  

1458
03:01:19,200 --> 03:01:21,760
and flew out to sea, far beyond their reach.

1459
03:01:22,960 --> 03:01:30,560
'This was a sign from the gods,' said Helen. 
'And its message seems clear. Just as the eagle  

1460
03:01:30,560 --> 03:01:35,680
attacked the chicken, Odysseus will attack 
the suitors when he finds his way home.  

1461
03:01:36,560 --> 03:01:40,480
Or perhaps he is already in 
Ithaca, planning their death.'

1462
03:01:42,000 --> 03:01:45,120
'I pray that you are right,' said Telemachus.  

1463
03:01:45,840 --> 03:01:49,360
And with a shout to the 
horses, he started the chariot.

1464
03:01:51,920 --> 03:01:55,680
After a smooth journey, they 
reached Pylos the next day.  

1465
03:01:57,040 --> 03:02:03,200
Telemachus said goodbye to Peisistratus at the 
port. 'I am sorry that I cannot say goodbye  

1466
03:02:03,200 --> 03:02:09,599
to your father too. But I have no time to go 
to the palace. I need to get home urgently.'

1467
03:02:11,600 --> 03:02:17,840
As the crew carried the gifts from Menelaus 
onto the ship, a stranger came to Telemachus.  

1468
03:02:19,439 --> 03:02:24,879
'Can you take me with you?' he 
asked. 'In Argos, my homeland,  

1469
03:02:25,600 --> 03:02:30,320
I have enemies who are trying to kill 
me. I think they have followed me here.'

1470
03:02:31,359 --> 03:02:36,719
'You are welcome to come with us,' replied 
Telemachus. 'We are going to Ithaca,  

1471
03:02:37,680 --> 03:02:39,520
and there you can stay as my guest.'

1472
03:02:40,960 --> 03:02:46,960
'I am grateful for your kindness, good 
friend,' said the stranger. 'My name  

1473
03:02:47,760 --> 03:02:52,720
is Theoclymenus. In Argos I am a famous prophet.'

1474
03:02:54,640 --> 03:03:00,000
They all climbed on board, and the crew pulled 
on their oars until Pylos was far behind them.  

1475
03:03:01,359 --> 03:03:08,399
In open sea, they put up the sail and the 
wind carried them quickly towards Ithaca. As  

1476
03:03:08,399 --> 03:03:13,519
Telemachus stared out at the waves, he wondered 
what would happen at the end of the voyage.  

1477
03:03:14,240 --> 03:03:19,359
Would he get home alive, or would the 
suitors succeed in their plan to murder him?

1478
03:03:23,279 --> 03:03:27,920
At the same time, Odysseus was having 
supper with Eumaeus in the hut.  

1479
03:03:29,279 --> 03:03:36,880
Wanting to test his host's loyalty, he said, 'I 
cannot take advantage of your kindness any longer.  

1480
03:03:37,840 --> 03:03:41,920
Tomorrow I will go to town and 
ask for work at the palace.  

1481
03:03:42,800 --> 03:03:47,279
And I can tell Queen Penelope that 
her husband will soon be home.'

1482
03:03:47,840 --> 03:03:56,240
'No, no!' replied Eumaeus. 'Penelope has listened 
to too many stories about Odysseus already.  

1483
03:03:57,200 --> 03:04:01,040
You would do no good. You would just upset her.  

1484
03:04:02,800 --> 03:04:06,160
And the suitors in the palace will 
not want you as their servant.  

1485
03:04:07,040 --> 03:04:13,120
They are surrounded only by good-looking young 
men with oil in their hair and handsome clothes.  

1486
03:04:14,080 --> 03:04:18,399
You might die a violent death if you 
went to the palace in search of work.  

1487
03:04:19,439 --> 03:04:28,080
No, it is better to stay here with me. When my 
master's son, Telemachus, returns from Pylos,  

1488
03:04:28,080 --> 03:04:32,080
he will give you some new clothes 
and send you wherever you want.'

1489
03:04:34,000 --> 03:04:36,479
'Your kindness continues, Eumaeus,'  

1490
03:04:37,439 --> 03:04:44,719
said his guest. 'I will wait for Telemachus 
s return as you suggest. But tell me,  

1491
03:04:45,520 --> 03:04:52,560
while I am here, about your masters family. 
Does he have a father or mother still living?'

1492
03:04:54,080 --> 03:05:00,960
'His father, Laertes, is still alive, 
but life brings him no happiness. He  

1493
03:05:00,960 --> 03:05:07,680
lost his son when Odysseus went to Troy, and 
then his dear wife died of a broken heart  

1494
03:05:07,680 --> 03:05:11,920
because of Odysseus's absence. 
She was a lovely woman.  

1495
03:05:13,040 --> 03:05:18,399
She was like a mother to me when I first 
came to Ithaca - I grew up in her house.'

1496
03:05:19,439 --> 03:05:25,200
'So you were still quite young when 
you came to Ithaca,' said Odysseus.

1497
03:05:26,399 --> 03:05:31,839
'What happened to you? How were you 
separated from your home and family?'

1498
03:05:32,720 --> 03:05:41,200
'Well, I was born in the far land of 
Syrie. My father, Ctesius, was its king.

1499
03:05:42,800 --> 03:05:48,400
One day a ship arrived from Phoenicia with 
lots of jewels and pretty things for sale.  

1500
03:05:49,840 --> 03:05:56,399
One of my father's servants was Phoenician. 
As a young girl, she had been stolen from  

1501
03:05:56,399 --> 03:06:02,879
her homeland by criminals. Now she was a 
tall, beautiful woman, good at her work,  

1502
03:06:03,680 --> 03:06:09,920
but not very sensible. Well, this servant fell 
in love with one of the Phoenician sailors.  

1503
03:06:10,800 --> 03:06:16,720
He offered to take her home with him to 
Phoenicia and she was very excited at the idea.  

1504
03:06:17,760 --> 03:06:22,960
But to pay for her voyage the sailors asked 
her to steal some gold from my father's palace.  

1505
03:06:24,640 --> 03:06:29,600
She agreed willingly, saying, "There is 
something else that I can give you too.  

1506
03:06:30,880 --> 03:06:38,240
At the palace I look after my master's young son. 
He is a clever boy and he follows me everywhere.  

1507
03:06:39,279 --> 03:06:44,399
If I brought him too, you could sell him 
for a high price at any foreign port."

1508
03:06:46,000 --> 03:06:52,080
'The plan was made. She left the palace 
secretly with a bag full of gold cups,  

1509
03:06:52,080 --> 03:06:58,880
and I, innocent child, went with 
her. But a few days into our voyage,  

1510
03:06:58,880 --> 03:07:05,520
the servant died suddenly on the ship. Her 
body was thrown to the fishes and I was left  

1511
03:07:05,520 --> 03:07:11,760
friendless. Later we came to Ithaca and 
Laertes bought me from the Phoenicians.'

1512
03:07:13,120 --> 03:07:20,880
'What a strange story of bad luck,' said 
Odysseus. 'I am sorry for your troubles.  

1513
03:07:21,600 --> 03:07:26,320
But you had good luck too, since 
you were bought by a kind master.'

1514
03:07:27,840 --> 03:07:30,640
Their conversation continued far into the night,  

1515
03:07:31,200 --> 03:07:37,840
until it was time to sleep. At the same 
time, Telemachus had had a lucky night.  

1516
03:07:38,560 --> 03:07:44,161
His ship was near the coast of Ithaca, and 
the crew had not seen the murderous suitors.

1517
03:07:45,439 --> 03:07:51,839
'Land on that beach,' he said to the men. 'I 
am going to get off there and visit my farms.  

1518
03:07:52,399 --> 03:08:00,879
Take the ship to the city without me.' He turned 
to one of the oarsmen, his loyal friend Peiraeus,  

1519
03:08:01,520 --> 03:08:08,640
and said, 'Could you give Theoclymenus a bed for 
the night? I will meet you in the city tomorrow.'

1520
03:08:10,399 --> 03:08:15,839
The crew took the ship onto the beach 
and Telemachus jumped out. He watched  

1521
03:08:15,840 --> 03:08:22,000
his companions as they sailed towards the city, 
then started along the path to Eumaeus's hut.

1522
03:08:25,439 --> 03:08:32,399
Eumaeus and Odysseus were preparing breakfast when 
Telemachus appeared in the doorway. Eumaeus jumped  

1523
03:08:32,399 --> 03:08:40,080
up in surprise, and the bowls in his hands fell 
noisily to the floor. He threw his arms around his  

1524
03:08:40,080 --> 03:08:45,920
young master like a loving father welcoming 
back his dear son after many years abroad.

1525
03:08:46,720 --> 03:08:49,440
'You are back, then, Telemachus!  

1526
03:08:50,319 --> 03:08:56,960
And I thought that I would never see you 
again after you sailed to Pylos. Come in,  

1527
03:08:57,520 --> 03:09:04,640
come in, dear child, and let me look at you. I 
do not see you often enough here on the farm.'

1528
03:09:06,000 --> 03:09:12,640
'It is good to see you too, Eumaeus. I have 
come here to ask for news from the palace.  

1529
03:09:13,920 --> 03:09:19,359
Is my mother still there, or has she married 
again and gone to her new husband's home?'

1530
03:09:20,319 --> 03:09:27,439
'She is still at the palace,' said the pig farmer. 
'And she still spends most of her days in tears.'

1531
03:09:28,960 --> 03:09:35,760
Telemachus came into the hut, and Odysseus stood 
up to give him his seat. But Telemachus stopped  

1532
03:09:35,760 --> 03:09:43,840
him. 'Please, stranger, do not get up. I am sure 
that there is something else for me to sit on.'

1533
03:09:45,200 --> 03:09:50,319
Eumaeus made another seat of sticks 
and sheepskin, and Telemachus sat  

1534
03:09:50,319 --> 03:09:57,920
down next to his father, Odysseus. 'So 
who is your guest, Eumaeus?' he asked.

1535
03:09:57,920 --> 03:10:02,800
'He is from Crete,' replied the 
servant, 'but he cannot go back there.  

1536
03:10:03,680 --> 03:10:06,720
I am hoping that you can look 
after him at the palace.'

1537
03:10:07,359 --> 03:10:15,679
'The palace?' cried Telemachus. 'But how can I? My 
mother is usually too upset to receive visitors,  

1538
03:10:16,319 --> 03:10:23,840
and the suitors are a dangerous crowd. I can 
do little to protect him against so many. I  

1539
03:10:23,840 --> 03:10:29,279
am happy to give him food and new clothes. 
And I will send him wherever he wants to go.  

1540
03:10:30,319 --> 03:10:36,479
But while he is in Ithaca he should stay 
here with you. It will be safer for him here.  

1541
03:10:38,160 --> 03:10:45,359
But now, Eumaeus, old friend, can I ask you to 
take a message to my mother? Tell her that I am  

1542
03:10:45,359 --> 03:10:52,239
back from Pylos. Tell no one except her. There 
are many people who are trying to harm me.'

1543
03:10:53,359 --> 03:10:59,040
Eumaeus wasted no time. He left the hut 
immediately in the direction of the palace.

1544
03:11:00,239 --> 03:11:07,040
Athene saw him go. She appeared suddenly at the 
door of the hut, although only Odysseus could  

1545
03:11:07,040 --> 03:11:14,560
see her. Odysseus followed her outside, where she 
said, 'It is time to tell your son who you are.  

1546
03:11:15,680 --> 03:11:21,840
Together you must start planning the fate 
of those men in your palace.' As she spoke,  

1547
03:11:22,479 --> 03:11:28,000
she took away his disguise of old age. 
His strength and good looks returned;  

1548
03:11:28,640 --> 03:11:33,440
his beard grew dark on his chin; 
and he was wearing fine new clothes.  

1549
03:11:34,640 --> 03:11:38,720
Then the goddess disappeared, and 
Odysseus went back into the hut.

1550
03:11:42,080 --> 03:11:51,279
Telemachus looked at him now in wonder. 'Stranger, 
you look completely different. Only the gods can  

1551
03:11:51,279 --> 03:11:57,359
change their appearance in this way. Which 
god are you, and what can I do for you?'

1552
03:11:58,720 --> 03:12:01,840
'I am not a god,' replied Odysseus.  

1553
03:12:02,960 --> 03:12:08,399
'But I am your father, who has been 
the cause of so many problems for you.'

1554
03:12:09,760 --> 03:12:13,200
He kissed his son, and tears ran down his face.  

1555
03:12:14,239 --> 03:12:20,880
But Telemachus stepped back from him. 
'You are not my father,' he said. 'A  

1556
03:12:20,880 --> 03:12:27,200
god is playing a cruel trick on me. No man can 
change his appearance as you have just done.'

1557
03:12:29,040 --> 03:12:31,840
'I promise you that this is no trick.  

1558
03:12:32,399 --> 03:12:37,920
My disguise was the work of Athene, who has 
been a great help to me in my troubles.'

1559
03:12:39,359 --> 03:12:41,920
Telemachus was satisfied by this answer.  

1560
03:12:42,960 --> 03:12:49,760
He threw his arms around his father's neck. 
Together they cried tears of great sadness and  

1561
03:12:49,760 --> 03:12:56,160
great happiness. This was the moment that 
they had both dreamt about for so many years.

1562
03:12:57,520 --> 03:13:02,640
'But how did you get to Ithaca?' 
Telemachus asked finally.

1563
03:13:04,319 --> 03:13:10,160
'In a Phaeacian ship. I have a great pile 
of treasure, which is hidden in a cave by  

1564
03:13:10,160 --> 03:13:16,000
the beach. But we should waste no time. 
We must plan the death of those suitors.  

1565
03:13:17,520 --> 03:13:22,081
Tell me how many of them there are. 
Then I can decide how to fight them.'

1566
03:13:23,600 --> 03:13:29,439
'There are more than a hundred suitors. I know 
that you have a great reputation as a soldier,  

1567
03:13:29,439 --> 03:13:32,879
Father. But we cannot possibly fight them alone.  

1568
03:13:34,000 --> 03:13:36,560
We must think of some people 
who will fight with us.'

1569
03:13:37,439 --> 03:13:44,000
'Athene and Zeus will fight with us,' his father 
replied. 'Their help will be enough, I think.'

1570
03:13:45,120 --> 03:13:50,000
'If you are right, then the suitors 
have no chance,' Telemachus agreed.

1571
03:13:51,200 --> 03:13:58,960
'Tomorrow,' continued Odysseus, you will go back 
to the palace. I will join you later in the day,  

1572
03:13:58,960 --> 03:14:06,720
disguised again as an old man. If the suitors 
are rough with me, do not worry. Their day of  

1573
03:14:06,720 --> 03:14:14,239
judgment is coming. But tell no one about my 
return - not my father Laertes, or Eumaeus,  

1574
03:14:14,239 --> 03:14:22,080
or even your mother. It must be a complete secret 
until we have destroyed the suitors' power.'

1575
03:14:23,200 --> 03:14:30,000
'We must do that very soon, or Mother will 
marry one of them. Then it will be too late.'

1576
03:14:31,840 --> 03:14:37,840
As father and son discussed their plans, 
Telemachus's crew arrived at the port in the city.  

1577
03:14:38,880 --> 03:14:45,520
A messenger was sent to tell Penelope that her 
son was safe. This messenger arrived at the palace  

1578
03:14:45,520 --> 03:14:51,840
at the same time as Eumaeus, and soon gave the 
queen his message in front of all her servants.  

1579
03:14:52,720 --> 03:14:58,880
In private, Eumaeus told her everything 
that he knew. Then he went back to his  

1580
03:14:58,880 --> 03:15:05,840
farm - to Telemachus and Odysseus, who 
Athene had changed back into an old man.

1581
03:15:07,200 --> 03:15:12,639
The news of Telemachus's return soon 
spread to the suitors, who were very angry.  

1582
03:15:13,520 --> 03:15:18,161
When Antinous's ship came into port, they 
rushed to find out what had happened.

1583
03:15:19,040 --> 03:15:27,040
'The lucky young fool!' shouted Antinous. 'My 
people were looking for him all along the coast,  

1584
03:15:28,000 --> 03:15:34,720
but he managed to get past us. We must find 
another way to kill him, and do it fast.  

1585
03:15:35,600 --> 03:15:41,280
If we do not, he will call another meeting 
and turn the people of Ithaca against us.  

1586
03:15:42,800 --> 03:15:49,360
They will not be happy that we have tried to 
murder their prince. If we are not careful,  

1587
03:15:50,319 --> 03:15:52,399
we will soon be thrown off this island.  

1588
03:15:53,520 --> 03:16:00,081
We have no choice. We must kill 
him now, before it is too late.'

1589
03:16:01,680 --> 03:16:11,120
Silence followed this speech. Finally, Amphinomus 
stood up to speak. He was a more thoughtful man  

1590
03:16:11,120 --> 03:16:19,359
than the rest, one of the few suitors who Penelope 
liked to talk to. 'My friends,' he said now,  

1591
03:16:20,319 --> 03:16:27,359
'I cannot agree to this murder. It is wrong to 
kill a prince, unless the gods have given clear  

1592
03:16:27,359 --> 03:16:34,399
signs that they want him dead. We should wait for 
those signs. Until then, we should do nothing.'

1593
03:16:35,840 --> 03:16:44,319
The other suitors agreed with him. For 
the moment, Telemachus was safe.
 
 
 

