Odysseus at the Palace

1596
03:16:48,560 --> 03:16:54,960
She quickly looked up at the stranger above 
her, and she knew - her master had returned.

1597
03:16:57,200 --> 03:17:01,359
The next morning, Telemachus prepared 
to visit his mother at the palace.  

1598
03:17:02,319 --> 03:17:05,759
As he left Eumaeus's hut, 
he said to the pig farmer,  

1599
03:17:06,560 --> 03:17:12,560
After I have gone, take our visitor to the 
city. He can ask the people there for food.'

1600
03:17:15,200 --> 03:17:20,960
Telemachus met the prophet Theoclymenus in 
town, then walked with him to the palace.  

1601
03:17:22,319 --> 03:17:28,559
Loyal old Eurycleia was the first to see her 
young master, and she ran up to him with a cry  

1602
03:17:28,560 --> 03:17:36,640
of happiness. The other servants followed, and 
finally Penelope came out of her room. Tears ran  

1603
03:17:36,640 --> 03:17:44,479
down her face as she threw her arms around him. 
'You are back, my child! And I thought I would  

1604
03:17:44,479 --> 03:17:51,519
never see you again after your secret departure. 
But come, tell me what you learnt on your voyage.'

1605
03:17:53,040 --> 03:18:00,800
'Well, we went first to Pylos. King Nestor 
received us kindly, but knew nothing about  

1606
03:18:00,800 --> 03:18:08,319
Odysseus's fate. He lent me a chariot, though, 
and with his son Peisistratus I went by land  

1607
03:18:08,319 --> 03:18:16,239
to Sparta and the palace of King Menelaus. 
During Menelaus's journey home from the war,  

1608
03:18:16,239 --> 03:18:21,840
he met the god Proteus. Proteus told 
him that my father was still alive,  

1609
03:18:22,560 --> 03:18:28,161
a prisoner on the goddess Calypso's island, 
without a ship or a crew to take him home.'

1610
03:18:30,640 --> 03:18:37,520
Telemachus's words warmed his mother's 
heart. Then his guest Theoclymenus added,  

1611
03:18:38,160 --> 03:18:47,599
'Great Penelope, Menelaus's information is old. 
Listen to my prophecy. Your husband Odysseus is  

1612
03:18:47,600 --> 03:18:54,720
already in Ithaca, studying his enemies, the 
suitors, and planning their day of judgment.'

1613
03:18:56,160 --> 03:18:59,519
'I pray that you are right,' replied Penelope.

1614
03:19:01,600 --> 03:19:07,920
Eumaeus and Odysseus were preparing to walk to 
the city. 'Are you sure you want to do this?'  

1615
03:19:08,479 --> 03:19:18,000
asked Eumaeus. 'The walk is not easy for a man of 
your age. Why not stay here in the hut instead?'

1616
03:19:18,000 --> 03:19:24,720
'Thank you, Eumaeus,' replied his guest. 
'But your young master Telemachus is right.  

1617
03:19:25,680 --> 03:19:32,400
It is time for me to go. Could I ask you, 
though, for a stick to help me walk?'  

1618
03:19:33,840 --> 03:19:37,200
Eumaeus got him a stick and 
they started their journey.  

1619
03:19:38,640 --> 03:19:46,080
The path was steep, but Odysseus went slowly and 
carefully and before long they came to a stream at  

1620
03:19:46,080 --> 03:19:53,120
the edge of the city. There they met Melanthius, 
who also looked after a farm on Odysseus's land.  

1621
03:19:54,160 --> 03:20:01,200
When this man saw Eumaeus, he immediately 
started shouting at him. 'Where are you  

1622
03:20:01,200 --> 03:20:08,559
going with that old ruin of a man? I hope you 
are not planning to take him to the palace.  

1623
03:20:09,520 --> 03:20:14,960
I doubt that he will manage a day in the 
suitors' company without broken bones.  

1624
03:20:15,920 --> 03:20:22,560
And the suitors are right too. He is a 
lazy fool who deserves nothing better.'

1625
03:20:24,880 --> 03:20:32,239
Melanthius then gave Odysseus a hard kick 
that almost knocked him over. As Odysseus was  

1626
03:20:32,239 --> 03:20:39,760
preparing to fight back, Eumaeus cried, 'Great 
Zeus, I pray that my master is returned to us.  

1627
03:20:40,640 --> 03:20:45,920
He would soon cure Melanthius of the arrogant 
ways that he has learnt from the suitors.'

1628
03:20:47,520 --> 03:20:55,040
Melanthius laughed as he walked away. 'Odysseus's 
chance of returning is as low as Telemachus s  

1629
03:20:55,040 --> 03:21:03,439
chance of escaping the suitors' violence. Things 
have changed, Eumaeus. You have new masters now.'

1630
03:21:08,080 --> 03:21:11,840
The pig farmer and the old man 
continued towards the palace.  

1631
03:21:12,960 --> 03:21:19,200
There was a dog called Argus lying 
near the gates. When he was younger,  

1632
03:21:19,200 --> 03:21:25,760
he had been an excellent hunting dog, trained 
by Odysseus himself and famous for his speed.

1633
03:21:27,040 --> 03:21:32,319
But now he was old and lay all day 
in the dust, alone and forgotten.  

1634
03:21:34,399 --> 03:21:40,000
When this dog heard the sound of Odysseus's 
voice, he lifted his head and moved his  

1635
03:21:40,000 --> 03:21:45,520
tail in excitement. He did not have the 
strength to get up and greet his master.  

